article.description: Janel McCarville had 18 points and guard Lindsay Whalen added 15 to help No. 17 Minnesota defeat No. 13 Penn State, 73-57, in a Big Ten matchup.
article.headline: Minnesota wins fifth straight game
article.linkText: Gophers gets a little revenge against Nittany Lions
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Asked how much an earlier 30-point loss at
Penn State served as motivation for Minnesota's rematch against the
Nittany Lions, Gophers center Janel McCarville answered: "90
percent.''

	   But Corrin Von Wald quickly corrected her.

	   "Ninety-nine percent,'' Von Wald said.

	   McCarville scored 18 points on 7-for-8 shooting to lead Minnesota (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 16 AP) to a 73-57 win over Penn State (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 12 AP) on
Sunday, preventing the Nittany Lions from clinching a share of the
Big Ten title.

	   Penn State (22-7, 12-3 Big Ten), which was held to a season-low
point total, can still clinch the title if it wins its final
regular-season game against Wisconsin on March 2.

	   The Gophers, who won their fifth straight, weren't as concerned
about the conference standings as they were about gaining revenge
for their earlier loss to the Lions, which was their first of the
season.

	   "We had something to prove today,'' McCarville said.

	   Lindsay Whalen scored 15 points for the Gophers (21-4, 10-4)
while Von Wald added 11 points. Both Whalen and Von Wald had six
assists.

	   The Gophers moved into a tie for second place in the conference
with Purdue, which lost to Ohio State 56-51 on Sunday.

	   Minnesota still has a chance to tie for the conference title if
Penn State loses to Wisconsin and the Gophers win their final two
games against the Badgers and at Michigan.

	   But the 83-53 loss to the Lions on Jan. 6 was their main
motivation.

	   "It's been a nightmare since we played Penn State,'' Gophers
coach Pam Borton said. "I told them, 'I don't know about you guys,
but that's left a bad taste in my mouth since we played them.'

	   "I don't think I had to say very much.''

	   Reserve Kim Prince scored all eight of her points late in the
first half to help spark a 23-4 run over the end of the first half
and beginning of the second that put Minnesota in control.

	   Tanisha Wright scored 17 points to lead Penn State.

	   The Gophers frustrated the Lions with their pressure defense,
trapping their opponents in the backcourt. Kelly Mazzante, the
nation's third-leading scorer who averaged 24.6 points per game and
had 22 points in Penn State's win over Minnesota, was held to 11
points -- two in the first half.

	   "It's probably the best defense we've faced this season,''
Lions coach Rene Portland said.

	   Mazzante was harassed all afternoon by Von Wald and the 6-foot-2
McCarville. On offense, Minnesota finished with 21 assists to Penn
State's 10.

	   Minnesota, which led by as many as 23 points, opened the second
half with 13 unanswered points on a series of short jumpers and
layups. Whalen had two layups off steals during the run.

	   McCarville hit a layup at the 15:19 mark to give the Gophers a
44-26 lead. Jess Strom's 3-pointer at the 14:36 mark finally ended
Penn State's drought.

	   "We didn't attack,'' Portland said. "We did a lot of standing
around, we weren't the typical Penn State team.''

	   The Lions tried to mount a comeback with a 12-4 spurt. But
Minnesota went back inside, getting some easy layups from
McCarville, Tanisha Gilbert, who had nine points, and Von Wald.

	   Von Wald had Minnesota's prettiest basket of the day, driving in
from the right side and spinning around a defender for a layup to
give the Gophers a 54-38 lead.

	   "Our defense creates offense,'' Whalen said. "We wanted to get
them frustrated at us, and it worked. We got them flustered.''
